  <div class="container">
    <h1>Claude Code Insights</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">21 messages across 3 sessions (22 total) | 2026-04-16 to 2026-05-02</p>

    
    <div class="at-a-glance">
      <div class="glance-title">At a Glance</div>
      <div class="glance-sections">
        <div class="glance-section"><strong>What's working:</strong> Your /init session that audited and updated CLAUDE.md is a standout—you&apos;re using it not just for setup but as an ongoing documentation maintenance tool, and Claude caught concrete issues like a stale script reference and missing invocation example in one pass. You&apos;re also comfortable interrupting mid-stream to ask clarifying questions, which keeps you unblocked rather than waiting things out. <a href="#section-wins" class="see-more">Impressive Things You Did →</a></div>
        <div class="glance-section"><strong>What's hindering you:</strong> On Claude&apos;s side, it sometimes proceeds with commands like /init in environments that won&apos;t yield useful results (e.g., empty directories) instead of pausing to confirm scope first. On your side, many sessions are spent cycling through configuration slash commands (/model, /theme, /chrome, /advisor) without ever issuing an actual task—this exploratory tinkering rarely converts into work, and mid-task meta-questions break flow on whatever you were doing. <a href="#section-friction" class="see-more">Where Things Go Wrong →</a></div>
        <div class="glance-section"><strong>Quick wins to try:</strong> Try defining a Custom Skill for your recurring documentation audits so /init-style reviews become a one-shot reusable command tuned to your standards. Also consider Task Agents for parallel work—spinning up sub-agents to explore different parts of a codebase simultaneously is a much higher-leverage use of a session than serial configuration tweaks. <a href="#section-features" class="see-more">Features to Try →</a></div>
        <div class="glance-section"><strong>Ambitious workflows:</strong> As models get stronger, point Claude at an unfamiliar repo and have it autonomously map architecture, run the build, fix what&apos;s broken, and produce a complete CLAUDE.md plus onboarding doc—turning hours of context-gathering into minutes. Parallel multi-agent codebase audits (security, dead code, test coverage, dependency drift synthesized into one backlog) will also become routine, replacing what used to be a week of senior review. <a href="#section-horizon" class="see-more">On the Horizon →</a></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    

