    <h2 id="section-usage">How You Use Claude Code</h2>
    <div class="narrative">
      <p>Your interaction pattern with Claude Code is dominated by <strong>configuration and exploration rather than actual task execution</strong>. Across 15 sessions, the overwhelming majority consisted of you cycling through local slash commands—`/chrome`, `/advisor`, `/mcp`, `/config`, `/keybindings`, model selectors, theme pickers, plan mode toggles—without ever issuing a substantive request to Claude. You appear to be in a <strong>persistent setup/tinkering mode</strong>, adjusting settings like effort level, TUI preferences, and plugin management, then exiting before giving Claude any real work. Many sessions ended with no actual prompt at all.</p>
<p>When you do engage Claude on tasks, you favor <strong>terse, command-driven invocations over detailed specs</strong>. Your most productive session was a simple `/init` that let Claude autonomously identify three issues in CLAUDE.md and fix them—you let it run without micromanaging. However, you&apos;re also willing to <strong>interrupt mid-execution</strong>: in one session you cut off Claude&apos;s bash call to pivot to a meta-question about disabling debug logging, suggesting you treat the session as fluid and won&apos;t hesitate to redirect when something more pressing comes to mind.</p>
<p>There&apos;s a notable <strong>mismatch between configuration effort and task output</strong>—you&apos;ve spent significant time customizing the environment but produced zero commits and only one fully-achieved task in the analyzed window. The `/init` on an empty directory further suggests you&apos;re sometimes invoking commands speculatively rather than with a clear codebase context in mind. Your style reads as someone still <strong>calibrating the tool itself</strong> rather than using it as a steady workhorse.</p>
      <div class="key-insight"><strong>Key pattern:</strong> You spend far more time configuring Claude Code via slash commands than actually delegating tasks to it.</div>
    </div>
    

