    <h2 id="section-friction">Where Things Go Wrong</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">Your sessions show a heavy pattern of cycling through configuration slash commands without ever giving Claude an actual task to perform.</p>
    <div class="friction-categories">
      
        <div class="friction-category">
          <div class="friction-title">Excessive configuration tinkering without follow-through</div>
          <div class="friction-desc">You spend many sessions cycling through local slash commands to tweak models, themes, plugins, and effort levels, then exit before asking Claude to do anything. Consider batching configuration changes once, then committing to an actual task in the same session.</div>
          <ul class="friction-examples"><li>You ran /advisor, /config, /chrome, and /mcp in sequence and then exited without any request, wasting the session entirely</li><li>You cycled through model selection commands and exited, meaning Claude never got to demonstrate value at the configured setting</li></ul>
        </div>
      
        <div class="friction-category">
          <div class="friction-title">Running commands in unsuitable environments</div>
          <div class="friction-desc">You invoke commands without first ensuring the workspace or environment supports them, leading to dead-end sessions. A quick check of your directory or platform compatibility before invoking would prevent these wasted runs.</div>
          <ul class="friction-examples"><li>You ran /init in an empty directory, so Claude had no code to analyze and you exited with nothing accomplished</li><li>You ran /terminal-setup in an unsupported environment and exited immediately afterward</li></ul>
        </div>
      
        <div class="friction-category">
          <div class="friction-title">Mid-task interruptions and context switches</div>
          <div class="friction-desc">You interrupt Claude&apos;s in-progress tool calls to ask unrelated meta-questions about the tool itself, breaking flow on the original task. Try noting these questions for after the current action completes, or ask them up front before kicking off work.</div>
          <ul class="friction-examples"><li>You interrupted a bash tool call mid-execution to ask how to disable debug logging, derailing the original task</li><li>Your slash-command-heavy sessions ended before any real task was attempted, suggesting you context-switch out before substantive work begins</li></ul>
        </div>
      
    </div>
    

